<docs>
	<doc for="FileAccess.Read">
		<summary>
			<para> Read access to the file.
      Data can be read from the file. Combine with <see langword="Write"/> for
      read/write access.</para>
		</summary>
	</doc>
	<doc for="FileAccess.Write">
		<summary>
			<para> Write access to the file.
      Data can be written to the file. Combine with <see langword="Read"/> for
      read/write access.</para>
		</summary>
	</doc>
	<doc for="FileAccess.ReadWrite">
		<summary>
			<para>Read and write access to the file. Data can be written
      to and read from the file.</para>
		</summary>
	</doc>
	<doc for="FileAccess">
		<summary>
			<para>Defines constants for read, write, or read/write access to a file.</para>
		</summary>
		<remarks>
			<para>For an example of creating a file and writing text to a
      file, see <see topic="cpconwritingtexttofile"/>.
      For an example of reading text from a file, see
   <see topic="cpconreadingtextfromfile"/>. For an
      example of reading from and writing to a binary file, see
   <see topic="cpconReadingWritingToNewlyCreatedDataFile"/>.</para>
			<para>A <see langword="FileAccess"/> parameter is specified in
   many of the constructors for <see cref="System.IO.File"/>, <see cref="System.IO.FileInfo"/>, <see cref="System.IO.FileStream"/> , and other constructors where it is important to
   control the kind of access users have to a file.</para>
		</remarks>
		<example>
			<para>The following <see langword="FileStream"/> constructor grants read-only access
   to an existing file (<see langword="FileAccess.Read"/>).</para>
			<codelink SampleID="Classic FileAccess Example" SnippetID="1"/>
		</example>
